  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "hh5w61AmXZiCZtbmgILWiOenI3g=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "The four storage layers differ on four independent axes. Knowing which axis a property sits on prevents mis-comparisons:\n\n| | PGlite | PostgreSQL | Swarm /bytes | Swarm feeds |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Lifespan** | Ephemeral (browser) | Persistent (server) | Until stamp expires | Until stamp expires |\n| **Mutability** | Mutable (can clear DB) | Mutable (can delete rows) | IMMUTABLE (content-addressed) | Append-only (each index write-once) |\n| **Who controls it** | User's browser | Server operator | Nobody (decentralized) | Feed owner (private key) |\n| **Auth required** | None (local) | API key / auth token | Postage stamp | Private key signature |\n\n**Axes summarized**:\n- **Ephemerality**: PGlite stands alone here. Everything else survives beyond a session.\n- **Mutability**: only local and server layers are truly mutable. Swarm is immutable at the chunk level; feeds add append-only mutability via indices.\n- **Control**: Swarm /bytes is the only layer nobody controls. Feeds are controlled by whoever holds the private key.\n- **Auth**: the auth story ranges from none (local) to server-gated (API key) to stamp-gated (network resource) to signature-gated (write capability).\n\n**Why this matters**: a statement like \"operations are duplicated to Swarm\" hides that the Swarm copy is immutable and no-operator-controlled \u2014 properties PostgreSQL cannot offer. Comparing copies on volume alone misses the whole point of the different layers.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:31.000Z"
    }
  },
